name: Andicuri
description:
Andicuri beach, is one of Aruba's number one surf spots. Mostly crowded by
bodyboarders it is a fun wedge type of wave. The wave is mostly a left
wedge but on big days the right jetty starts working. It's the most
consistent spot on the island with some nice hollow barrels and very fun
wedging ramps. It's for every level but on big days, experience is a must
because the wave gets very steep and throws really fast on the dry sand
bottom. Rides are generally short, but with good swell direction the side
waves get longer and connect better with the oncoming waves.

name: Dos Playas
description:
One of the better known spots on Aruba, both for bodyboarding and surfing, Dos
Playa is located on the north coast in the Natural Reserve Park Arikok and
is easily accessible. The name Dos Playa translates literally to "Two
Beaches" because there are two large bays separated by large cliffs. The
wave is a beach break that breaks really close to the shore. The waves
breaks left and right giving some of the most consistent surfing on the
island.This spot is prone to bigger swells and is really hollow and
powerful and offers big ramps and big barrels. On big days is not
recommended for beginners.

name: Druif
description:
Boca Druif, located behind the Tierra del Sol golf course, is a slab that doubles up on itself.
Strictly a bodyboarding wave but some surfers have been known to charge it
on the good offshore days. It breaks on a very shallow reef and is very
steep, hollow and powerful. The main peak is mostly lefts but because it is
a very wide bay it offers some rights. On the far right side of the bay
there is jetty that turns into a sick little right hander wedge. On average
onshore days the wave is still pretty hollow and barreling but with shorter
rides. This spot prefers a north swell with low or south winds in order
to really turn on with long, big and hollow lefts. This spot is for
experienced surfers only and is usually uncrowded.

name: Dunes/Dooms
description:
One of the most picturesque of surfing spots on Aruba. Rarely busy, even
on weekends, Dunes or Dooms as the locals call it, is a classic surfing
spot. Behind you is wide beach, with a rugged coastline, and rustic
lighthouse; in front of you the never ending blue. It breaks over shallow
reef and can hold very big waves. Swells can get up to 7 or 8 feet if your
lucky. This is the go-to spot on those elusive after-hurricane swells.
Dangerous though. There is no channel whatsoever so you have to paddle
straight out through the white water . Sea urchins, rips, undertow and
rocks rule the area. This spot is for your average surfer but on big days
experience is a must.

name: Urirama
description:
A classic reef rocky spot, Urirama is a really small bay/inlet, located
near the old Alto Vista Chapel on the north coast. It is mostly a left and
very shallow with waves breaking all the way in to the small bay. Some waves
break in front of the rocky coast line.On good swell directions, waves
break both left and right, with good swells getting up to 5 or 6 feet. With
offshore winds, the waves turn on and are very hollow. The rocky coast line
provide some dangers because some waves break right in front of it. Don't
get caught inside.

name: Wariruri
description:
Wariruri is a bay located near the Bushiribana Goldmine Ruins on the
north coast of the island. A popular spot among surfers, Wariruri is a
place for all levels. Waves break both left and right and can reach faces
as high as six feet some times bigger. There are rocks on the left side and
far right side but other than that, it's a pretty good rippable wave with
good sections. On big days, the current can get strong and it can be
difficult to get out in to the line up. On the far left side of the bay,
there is a left peak which breaks on dry reef. Don't get caught on the left
side of the bay or you'll be into the rocks.

name: Majon Hotel Beach
description:
Located just east of Hamhung (DPRK's second biggest city after Pyongyang), this private beach lays just in front of the Majon Hotel (a 5-star Sheraton). The beach benefits from the frequent easterly swells that approach the coast of North Korea. The emerald bay offers two different surf locations: an easy beach break-peak and a juicy sand-bottom point-break. This is the home of Majon Surf School and where we do most of our free-surfing and lessons. 

CRYSTALS was named after local surfer girl, Kim Jin Ok (meaning “True Crystals”), and is a choreographic, fast point-break peeling under an imposing ferrous headland, on the southern corner of Majon Bay. It activates with swell from NE, E and SE, starting from 0.8m on forecasts. The wave offers a shifty, punchy takeoff just under the cliff, followed by an easy second section that leads to a zippy inside, often connecting all the way to the shore for a total ride of over 70-100m. The bottom is made of compact, thick-grain sand, with some scattered rocks that do not constitute a hazard. The point activates at high tide, and can be surfed with onshore winds up to 8-10knt. The spot offers a deep water channel (with a moderate outgoing rip) just aside of the break for easy access to take off zone. Visible from your room window at Majon Hotel, this is the highest quality wave discovered so far in North Korea. 

FLOWERS was named after local surfer girl, Kim Kook Hwa (meaning “National Flower”), and is a mellow sand bottom peak right in front of the beach house of the Majon Surf School. The slowly decreasing bathymetry here makes this sandbank a good long-boarding and SUP wave and a perfect venue for surf lessons. Instructors can safely operate in belly to chest high water, comfortably helping students with assisted take offs, 40-70m from the shore.  Flowers activates on minimal swells (from 0.4m up on forecasts), especially at low tide when it produces a clean A-frame peak, with 50m long lefts and rights. With bigger swells the spot turns into a high-performance beach break, with rippable walls and steep sections.

name: Pioneers
description: “Pioneers” was named by Kim Wang Sun, DPRK’s first official surfer. This was the first break surfed in the DPRK and is located in the next bay north of Majon Beach. The compact-sand breach break offers punchy lefts and rights depending on size and swell direction. Breaks on NE, E and SE swells from 0.5m up.  Good for beginners, longboarding and SUP’s on smaller days. Good for shortboarding and bodyboarding on larger days when it gets steep and hollow, connecting all the way to the inside.

When flat, Sijung turns into a great SUP destination, with picturesque offshore islets and a beautiful fresh water lake to be explored

name: Beadnell Bay
description:
The Bay can accommodate swells upto 12-15ft in size. Usually you choose the Bay due to its favorable wind directions and protected swell. The North end of the Bay needs a big (5ft+) south/south-easterly swell to work well. The middle of the Bay can produce excellent waves through most swell directions and sizes. The far south of the Bay is more open and holds big open northerly swells.

The Carrs reef in the midde of the Bay produces a left and a right that can hold swell upto 10ft easily and can result in quality 150 yard rides.

Always try and get the central to north end of the Bay on the pushing or high tide, the banks are better an the swell gets into the beach over the reefs more easily.

The Carrs reefs need a high tide to work and soon become exposed about an hour and a half after high.

It works on all stages of tide, but best a couple hours either side of low, tends to have a closing out beach break at high tide.North sea swell from NW through to E is best, but can have a wave on a strong S-SW channel swell. Manorbier is a consistent and well-known break surfed regularly throughout the year.

name: Pacitan
description:
Pacitan is small seaside town 2.5 hours drive away from the Central
Java city of Jogjakarta. A strip of white sand beach lines the bay
from the river and cliff to the east to the hill and small harbor to
the west. There are several spots to surf within the bay, mostly
beach breaks but a couple of sand covered reef type breaks too. Good
for beginning to intermediate surfers. There are several other surf
spots further west up the coast as well. Ask the friendly locals to
show you around. Beachside accommodations are available but limited,
most hotels being closer to the downtown area, 5-10 minutes drive to
the beach.

name: Darne
description: A reef break located just behind l'Ile des Deux Cocos. It's a isolated and beautiful place with a wonderful landscape. The wave runs for about 25 to 75m with some barrels when the wind turns north, offshore, no wind or with a big swell. It starts to work at 2ft to 8ft+. At low tide its shallow and so it can be dangerous and the current can be strong in the pass.The best season is summer but in winter when the wind is light you can have some nice sessions. The best swell direction is south-east and east, with a south or south-west swell the waves close out.
